Regression Models Course Project

Andrew Clarkson

September 18, 2016

Executive Summary

This analysis seeks to shed light on the question, Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG. After careful exploration and modeling, the conclusion to be taken from this data set is that the type of transmission does not effect the MPG.

Effect of Transmission on MPG

By creating a regression model we can see that transmission appears to have a very strong effect on MPG. These results can be interpreted as saying: By switching from automatic to manual you should expect to gain 7.244939 MPG. In the summary we can glean, that ams p value is fairly low at 0.000285. This would suggest the am variable is fairly significant to MPG.

fit <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)

summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -9.3923 -3.0923 -0.2974  3.2439  9.5077 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   17.147      1.125  15.247 1.13e-15 ***
## am             7.245      1.764   4.106 0.000285 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.902 on 30 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3598, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3385 
## F-statistic: 16.86 on 1 and 30 DF,  p-value: 0.000285

We can also calculate the confidence interval for the model. This interval we can interpret as saying with 95% confidence we can say the gains will be between 3.64151 and 10.84837

confint(fit, 'am', level=0.95)
##      2.5 %   97.5 %
## am 3.64151 10.84837

The issue with this model is that it doesnt explain much of the variation as evidenced by the relatively low R squared value of 0.3598. So while all the other pieces appear to line up there appears to be fairly large residuals.

Significance of Weight on MPG

Of the variables that might influence MPG, weight is the most logically direct. Heavier car, lower MPG. Using a simple plot one can visually pick up on the strong inverse relationship between MPG and weight.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(
  aes(x = wt, 
      y = mpg, 
      color = factor(am, labels = c("automatic","manual"))), 
  data = mtcars
  ) + 
  geom_point() + 
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Transmission") + 
  xlab("Weight") + 
  ylab("MPG")

Factoring in weight

In order to fully understand the transmissions effect on MPG, we must pick out weight and measure its effect while holding weight constant. By adding weight as a confounding variable in the regression model, we can tease apart transmissions true effect.

fit2 <- lm(mpg ~ am + wt, data = mtcars)
intercept <- fit2$coefficients[1]
slope <- fit2$coefficients[2]
summary(fit2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ am + wt, data = mtcars)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.5295 -2.3619 -0.1317  1.4025  6.8782 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 37.32155    3.05464  12.218 5.84e-13 ***
## am          -0.02362    1.54565  -0.015    0.988    
## wt          -5.35281    0.78824  -6.791 1.87e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 3.098 on 29 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7528, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7358 
## F-statistic: 44.17 on 2 and 29 DF,  p-value: 1.579e-09

As we can see from the summary the p value for the transmission variable went up dramatically by adding in weight. This can be interpretted as am losing relative significance. With the p value that high, we cannot reject the null hypothesis. Simply put this analysis suggests the transmission isnt relevant.

As would be expected by adding more variables to the model. More variance can be explained as evidenced by the R squared value.

summary(fit2)$r.squared
## [1] 0.7528348

Residuals and Diagnostics

In order to understand the model, various residual focused tools can be used. The first is the standard set of residual plots.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit2)

From this we can glean that the residuals of the model are relatively normally distributed (as evidenced by the Normal Q-Q plot). This suggests our model isnt significantly biased. We can see that there are a few points that stick out from the others. Examining these data points in detail yields a few interesting results.

mtcars[rownames(mtcars) %in% c("Ford Pantera L", "Merc 230", "Fiat 128"), ]
##                 mpg cyl  disp  hp drat   wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Merc 230       22.8   4 140.8  95 3.92 3.15 22.90  1  0    4    2
## Fiat 128       32.4   4  78.7  66 4.08 2.20 19.47  1  1    4    1
## Ford Pantera L 15.8   8 351.0 264 4.22 3.17 14.50  0  1    5    4
diagnostics <- data.frame(dfbetaam = dfbeta(fit2)[,2], hat = hatvalues(fit2), am = mtcars$am, wt = mtcars$wt, mpg = mtcars$mpg)

diagnostics[rownames(diagnostics) %in% c("Toyota Corolla", "Chrysler Imperial", "Fiat 128"), ]
##                    dfbetaam        hat am    wt  mpg
## Chrysler Imperial 0.6542817 0.21345363  0 5.345 14.7
## Fiat 128          0.4363322 0.07980538  1 2.200 32.4
## Toyota Corolla    0.1873090 0.09840238  1 1.835 33.9

From these diagnostics, we can see that the Chrysler Imperial appears to be a very influencial point. It has relatively low MPG and is an automatic, but also is one of the heaviest cars in the data set. In contrast, the Toyota Corolla has a relatively high MPG, and while it is a manual transmission, it is also one of the lightest cars in the dataset.

Results

Based on the models and tools used in this analysis, MPG is not influenced strongly by the difference between automatic and manual, but is instead heavily influenced by weight. A model that does not consider weight when looking at MPG could easily draw the wrong conclusions.
